factoids: The Hawkins National Laboratory seems to conduct unusual experiments." lends undue doubt to something we know to have happened.

page_id: Prefer nonjudgmental language. "Martin Brenner is pure evil." is a judgement by moral standards that are not shared by the entire readership.

Verifiability on {{SITENAME}} is the readers ability to check [[Stranger Things Wiki:Citation|cited sources]] that directly support the information in an article. All objective information in {{SITENAME}} must be verifiable
page_title: but because other policies and guidelines also influence content
page_ns: verifiability does not guarantee inclusion. Verifiability
timestamp: is one of the fundamental requirements for inclusion in {{SITENAME}}; truth
contributor_name: is not a substitute for meeting the verifiability requirement. No matter how convinced you are that something is true
bytes: do not add it unless it is verifiable. Information supported by actual broadcast episodes
column10: are considered implicitly verified when (and only when) the episode is actually broadcast for the first time.

page_id: It must be possible to attribute all information in {{SITENAME}} to reliable
page_title: published sources that are appropriate for the content in question. However
page_ns: in practice it is only necessary to provide inline citations for quotations and for any information that has been challenged or that is likely to be challenged. Appropriate citations guarantee that the information is not [[#Original research|original research]]
revision_id: and allow readers and editors to check the source material for themselves. Any material that requires a citation but does not have one may be removed. For help on adding citations
timestamp: see [[Stranger Things Wiki:Citation|Citing sources]]. This policy applies to all objective material in the mainspace (Episode Pages

page_id: In terms of Spoilers and Commentary pages
page_title: text and pictures from articles may be copied into the site ONLY IF the work referenced has attribution.
proper licensure and source is expected. Just being "out there on the Internet" does not make a photo free to use on this Wiki!

page_id: The term "original research" (OR) is used on {{SITENAME}} to refer to material—such as facts
revision_id: published sources exist. This includes any analysis or synthesis of published material that serves to advance a position not advanced by the sources. To demonstrate that you are not adding OR
timestamp: you must be able to cite reliable
contributor_id: published sources that are directly related to the topic of the article
contributor_name: and directly support the material being presented (and as presented).

page_id: The prohibition against OR means that all material added to articles must be attributable to a reliable published source
page_title: even if not actually attributed. The verifiability policy says that an inline citation to a reliable source must be provided for all quotations
page_ns: and for anything challenged or likely to be challenged—but a source must exist even for material that is never challenged. That "Paris is the capital of France" needs no source
revision_id: because no one is likely to object to it and we know that sources exist for it. The statement is attributable

page_id: Despite the need to attribute content to reliable sources
page_title: you must not plagiarize them or violate their copyrights. Articles should be written in your own words while substantially retaining the meaning of the source material.

page_id: There are very few policies which apply across all Wikia. These can be found on the Central Wikia at [[Wikia:Category:Policy]].
Other policies for this Wikia are usually decided by the wiki community in a consensus vote.

factoids: The Article Layout Guide shows how articles should be structured and organized on the wiki. This page will explain the organization of different types of articles
column10: as well as how to properly add content to each section.

page_id: Character Pages should more or less follow this layout:
Some of the sections included on the above list are optional. Some characters may even need additional sections depending on the information.

page_title: the characters actions throughout the series will be described.
excluding those that are included in the Background subsection
page_ns: should be written in the order that they happened in the story.

page_id: All information should be recorded as it was presented in series. No speculation or opinions should be present in this section.
The events should focus on the character whose page you are writing it for.
The events should also be written inuniverse and in past tense:
Mike played Dungeons & Dragons with his friends in the basement.

page_title: Mike is playing Dungeons & Dragons with his friends in the basement.

page_id: This section consists of events that took place in the characters life before the start of the series.
Events that are shown in flashbacks should be included in this section.

page_title: this subsection may be divided into different sections. For example
page_ns: Elevens background is split into Birth and Early Life and Psychokinetic Training.

page_id: Some characters may not have this subsection due to there being no information about their past.
Here is where the events that took place in the current timeline of the story. This section is usually what takes up a majority of the article.
Be descriptive. Dont overly summarize events.
Make sure to include all events. Even if the character only appeared in the background in a scene
Here the qualities of the characters personality will be described. This section may sometimes be called Personality and Traits.
Its not enough to just say a character is brave. Give some examples of the characters bravery.
The characters likes and dislikes can be noted here.

page_ns: and mannerisms can also go here.

page_id: Here is where the characters relationships will be described. Basically
This section usually has two subsections:
Familial  This can also include adopted and surrogate relationships.
NonFamilial  this includes all other relationships that are not part of the characters family. Friends
revision_id: and other relationships should go here.

page_id: The relationships should be written mostly from the perspective of the character youre writing it for.
Only notable relationships should be described here. While Holly Wheeler is Mikes sister
page_title: not much has been shown of them interacting
page_ns: so Holly should not be included in this section on Mikes page.

page_id: One common problem with writing this section is that some interactions between characters may have different meanings and interpretations to other people. As a result
page_title: it is sometimes easy to get carried away with personal opinions. Please avoid this as much as possible and instead focus on how the characters relationships were meant to be depicted in the story.

page_id: If at any point this section becomes too lengthy
page_title: then it should be moved to a separate page.

page_id: This is where the characters episode appearances are noted. Usually
page_title: this section only consists of the Season Appearance templates.
please view the Templates section below.

page_id: Here notable things said by the character will be listed. The quotes should be placed with bullet points and have quotations marks.
The Quotes should be important and have impact.
Behind the Scenes is a section for "realworld" facts. Facts about casting and the characters creation should be written here. This section should be written in paragraphs
page_ns: it should not be written from an inuniverse point of view.

page_id: Trivia is a collection of interesting
page_title: often little known facts about the character. All facts should be written in bullet points. This section can include:

page_id: Observations made about the character by observing background clues or hints present in dialogue.
Facts revealed about the character in interviews
Acknowledgment of fan reactions and fan theories.
This section is also one of the few sections where speculation is somewhat acceptable
page_title: as long as it is made clear that it has not been confirmed.

page_id: Galleries are to display interesting images. In this case
page_title: the gallery will display images of the character during interesting or major situations.

page_id: <nowiki>{{</nowiki>[[Template:GalNote|GalNote]]<nowiki>}}</nowiki> — This appears at the top of the page and displays the rules of adding photos to the galleries. This template should be added to the page before anything else.

The <nowiki>{{</nowiki>[[Template:Episode|Episode]]<nowiki>}}</nowiki> infobox should be used. Episode pages should be placed in [[:Category:Episodes]] and any appropriate subcategories. The <nowiki>{{</nowiki>[[Template:Navbox/Episode|Navbox/Episode]]<nowiki>}}</nowiki> template should be placed at the end of every article.
Episode pages should more or less follow this layout:
Note: Some episodes may not have enough enough information for all of the sections included on the above list. Some episodes may even need additional sections depending on the information.
Synopsis — A brief summary of the episode. The official synopsis written for the episode on the Netflix website should be written here.
Plot — This section is much like the History section on character pages
page_title: only this time you will just describe what happened in a single episode
page_ns: as well as the storylines of all characters.

page_id: All events should be written in the order that they happened in the episode.
All information should be recorded as it was presented in the episode. No speculation or opinions should be present.
No information from future episodes should be present.
Events should be written in present tense and inuniverse.
Cast — Here all of the cast members that appeared in the episode will be listed alongside their characters. Major cast members should be listed first.
Music — All the music heard in the episode will be listed here.
This section will have two subsections:
Soundtrack  All songs produced by others artists
Original Score  All songs produced specifically for the show by Kyle Dixon and Michael Stein.
All songs should have a short description of the scene where they were heard.
Notes — Interesting facts and notes about the episode.
Gallery — A collection of interesting images from the episode.
References — A list of sources for information used in the article.
The <nowiki>{{</nowiki>[[Template:Season|Season]]<nowiki>}}</nowiki> infobox should be used. Season pages should be placed in [[:Category:Seasons]] and any appropriate subcategories.
Season pages should more or less follow this layout:
Note: Additional sections may need to be added depending on the information.
Synopsis  A brief summary of the season. The official synopsis written on the Netflix website should be written here.
Plot summary  A condensed description of the seasons plot. This section should be written in present tense.
Cast and characters  A list of the cast and their characters
page_title: along with how many episodes they appear in

page_id: Main cast  All major cast members and their characters.
Recurring cast  Recurring cast members and their characters.
Episodes  The seasons episodes displayed in a table. The table should include an image from each episode
page_title: as well as each episodes title

page_id: Development  Anything relating to the development of the season
revision_id: and casting. Each aspect of development should be its own subsection. Subsections may vary.

page_id: Production  Anything relating to the production of the season
page_title: such as filming and special effects.

page_id: Filming  Any details about the seasons filming
page_title: such as schedules and filming of particular scenes.

page_id: Special effects  Any details about how the seasons SFX were accomplished.
Music  Details about the music used in the season. Can include details about both the original score
Marketing  Advertising for the season. This section may consist of the seasons trailers or posters from social media marketing campaigns.
While all other page types on the wiki dont have specific layouts that should be followed
page_title: it is important that they still follow the wikis guidelines and maintain a certain level of consistency.

factoids: It is highly possible that an article has far too many images that they overshadow the significance of the article. The editors here should strive for a tasteful array
column10: rather than a garish smorgasbord of images. Such displays should be curated to the most significant
column12: or best images; either that or they must be arranged and organized in a better manner than the current gallery
column14: or table (or lack of these elements!) provides. This can even apply to Media subpages; just because they are in the right place doesnt mean they should be disorganized.

page_id: When uploading or embedding a media file
page_title: it is good practice to name the file something significant so that it is easy to find later.

page_id: : Screencaps should use "File:S01E01 Description" format where possible. Admins are able to rename items in the File: namespace. If you upload a lot of material
page_title: and your File: names do not conform to this policy
page_ns: you will be directed to this page.

page_id: :Other than screencaps: Aim for being descriptive where possible.
:"Video:Teaser S01E99" is the preferred format for directly episode related material
page_title: and whatever description is appropriate. Put the episode number in front if its a scene from the episode
page_ns: but after if its a video about an episode. This makes finding them later much easier.

page_id: Keep in mind that you cant use the "#" mark in the title
page_title: and use of punctuation should be avoided in the title.

page_id: Video:See a sneak preview of the thirteenth episode of Stranger Things
Video:Stranger Things on Netflix  The Duffer Brothers talk about their show Stranger Things to a reporter

page_title: as you might expect: Categories. File: and Video: items have their own pages for description
timestamp: etc. They can also be placed into categories

page_id: Quotations help to liven up a page
page_title: using dialogue from characters to help "set the scene" of a section
page_ns: so to speak. Quotations are created through the use of quotation templates (namely {{tl|Dialogue}} and {{tl|Line}}). An overuse of quotes can make an article look very sloppy. This is particularly enforced on good articles and featured articles.

page_id: These should only be applied if one can actually say something relevant about all members of the group as a generalization. In the Category:Students example
page_title: there are things that can be said about the entirety of the members (the rules and mythology of ghosts in this shows paradigm). The same cant be said of ALL male vs female characters. Ditto main vs recurring vs guest. Overorganization can become an easy compulsion to follow.

page_id: Adding categories like "Sex" and "Teen Angst" to a page
page_ns: is also not very helpful. Articles are not like blog posts where they require as many tags as possible. The category system was not designed to be used as thematic tags like keywords
contributor_id: and site navigation. The extraneous tags make administration and navigation more difficult.

page_id: Following these guidelines may seem like a daunting task for users who are new to wikis and the encyclopedic format. We understand that
page_title: and it is perfectly normal that some people may be confused. To ease this confusion
page_ns: the admins and many contributors are very willing to help anyone who needs it and asks for it. That last point
contributor_id: because we have no way of knowing if you want help unless you seek it.

page_id: Are you ready for a new adventure?
Follow the instructions of our Dungeon Master and complete your own path. Hawkins is in danger!
There are 3 different paths with three different characters: a police man
page_title: a worried mom and a russian scientist. Choose your character
page_ns: name it and reach the end of the story to earn a chance to win a prize!

page_id: You have to write your email address correctly in the beginning of the scavenger hunt if you want to have a chance to win the prize. An email address can participate once.

page_id: A typical reference should follow this format:
When or When Not to Create an Article
While its true that the wikis purpose is to be a place to house and obtain information
page_title: its important to remember that this is the Stranger Things wiki. All articles on this wiki must be related and relevant to [[Stranger Things]]. However
page_ns: that does not mean that every single character or item mentioned in the series is necessarily important enough to get their own page. The series also often has references to reallife people and media
revision_id: especially those that inspired it. While these references are interesting and should definitely be mentioned
timestamp: that doesnt mean they warrant their own article.

page_id: Relevancy: This will be the main factor when figuring out if a subject should have its own page. Was the subject relevant to the show/story? Did it play a major role
page_title: or was it just mentioned in a passing line of dialogue? The [[sensory deprivation tank]] deserves its own article because it played a vital role in the story; it was how Eleven entered her mental void where she made contact with the Monster
page_ns: opening the rift to the Upside Down. Meanwhile
revision_id: the [[Atari]] doesnt get its own article because it was only mentioned and not important to the story.

page_id: Information: Is there enough information on the subject to warrant an article? If only two or three sentences can be written about the subject
page_title: odds are it shouldnt have an article.

page_id: Integration: While the subject may not require its own article
page_title: that doesnt mean it shouldnt be mentioned at all. If the subject is related to another bigger
revision_id: then it can be integrated somewhere on that topics article either as its own section or a subsection.

page_title: if there are multiple similar subjects that alone do not have enough information
page_ns: they can be combined into a single article.

page_id: Please keep in mind that some of the policies on this page are subject to change.
One majority of the wikis content will simply be derived from the source material
page_title: while the other majority will be from interviews and other official statements from the cast and crew.

page_id: Any information on this wiki must be verifiable and come from official sources. Those sources must be cited.
All information must be officially revealed. No information from leaks or untrustworthy sources will be permitted on the wiki.
This wiki focuses on canon. This is not a place for fanon content
page_title: with the only exception being for use on User profiles.

page_ns: or opinions should be absent from main article sections. If something is ambiguous in the series
revision_id: then it should be ambiguous on the wiki.

page_id: Minimal speculation or interpretation should only be applied when necessary and must be somewhat supported by hints present in canon.
Fullyfledged theories may only be permitted in designated "Theories" sections.
Keep in mind when writing for articles that the main purpose is to record information. The writing should be comprehensible
page_title: but not too overly complicated or "fancy".

page_id: Formal language should be used. Avoid using any slang or overly casual tones.
Articles should be written from a neutral point of view (NPOV) even when writing for antagonists or describing acts that could be seen as malicious.
Please avoid simply tacking sentences on to the ends of paragraphs.  Instead
page_title: try to integrate the sentence where it belongs in the paragraph
page_ns: or even rewrite the paragraph to include the information.

page_id: Episode pages should be written in present tense.

page_title: as well as most other pages
page_ns: should be written in past tense. Exceptions to this are trivia sections
revision_id: and any other section where present tense is necessary.

page_id: In order to maintain some style and consistency across articles
page_title: we should have a set standard on which tense they should be written in. There is a tiny little mention in the MoS about this
page_ns: but its not really official (or entirely clear for that matter). I think the community needs to agree to a standard and stick to it.

page_id: I think articles about things that exist "inside" the shows universe (characters
revision_id: etc.) should be written in the past tense. Were writing about events from 1983
timestamp: after all. Writing in the present tense reads like a plot summary
contributor_id: and reading about the history of a person or thing as if it is happening in real time is not customary and feels very strange. —[[User:80XPD|80XPD]] ([[User talk:80XPD|talk]]) 21:25

page_title: sansserif;fontsize:14px;">An infobox is a template that displays as a labeled box along the righthand margin of an article and contains short
page_ns: labeled data. It sometimes contains data that is not displayed and is used in other parts of the Wiki. Typically
revision_id: placing an Infobox of one of the standard forms will place the article into the appropriate categories. Not everyone can see the Infobox. This is especially true of mobile browsers and screen readers. The Infobox should not ever be counted on as the sole source of a piece of information. It is also painfully easy to delete by mistake.

page_title: sansserif;fontsize:14px;">Banners are templates that display as an elongated
page_ns: horizontal box. They usually signify a notice about the article or following section. In Source view
revision_id: banners should always be placed on their own line.

page_title: sansserif;fontsize:14px;">This section should identify the topic of the article and place it into context. It may also include a basic description.

page_id: Mystery Science Theater 3000’s national broadcast life began in 1989. Set on the Satellite of Love where a human host is trapped by mad scientists with his two robot sidekicks and forced to watch an endless run of B movies. The format proved to be popular
page_title: and during its eleven years and 198 episodes on the Comedy Channel and SciFi Channel
page_ns: it attained a loyal fan base and critical acclaim
revision_id: including a Peabody Award and two Emmys® nominations.

the "new link"  all while keeping the redonblack contrast ratio
high enough for people of varying visual acuities able to read the page.

so that theres no odd grey streak at the bottom

:{{hatnote|Example hatnote text.}} →

page_title: a hatnote should answer a readers question (maybe preemptively): Am I on the right page?

page_id: This template is primarily used to add a correctly formatted hatnote to a page. Often
page_ns: this is a disambiguation link at the top of article pages. It places an HTML div / div block around the text entered as its only argument
revision_id: which provides standardized formatting (contents are indented and italicized in most displays); it also isolates the contained code to make sure that it is interpreted correctly.

page_id: This template is also used as the "metatemplate" for additional specialized disambiguation link templates; see [[:Category:Hatnote templates]] for a list.
The template does not automatically create links of any kind. Links and other desired formatting must be explicitly added
This template accepts the following parameters:
extraclasses any extra CSS classes to be added. For example
page_title: the {{t|see also}} template adds the classes boilerplate seealso.

revision_id: adds the CSS class "selfref". This is used to denote selfreferences.

timestamp: suppresses the error tracking category ([[:Category:Hatnote templates with errors]]). This only has an effect if the first positional parameter (the hatnote text) is omitted.

page_id: If no hatnote text is supplied
page_title: the template will output the following message:

page_id: If you see this error message
page_title: it is for one of four reasons:

page_id: # No parameters were specified (the template code was {{hatnote}}). Please use {{hatnote|text}} instead.

page_title: but the hatnote text wasnt included. For example
page_ns: the template text {{hatnote|extraclassesseealso}} will produce this error. Please use (for example) {{hatnote|text|extraclassesseealso}} instead.

page_title: but that text contains an equals sign (""). The equals sign has a special meaning in template code
page_ns: and because of this it cannot be used in template parameters that do not specify a parameter name. For example
revision_id: the template code {{hatnote|2+24}} will produce this error. To work around this
timestamp: you can specify the parameter name explicitly by using 1 before the hatnote text

page_id: # You tried to access [[Module:Hatnote]] directly by using {{#invoke:hatnote|hatnote|text}}. Use of #invoke in this way has been disabled for performance reasons. Please use {{hatnote|text}} instead.
If you see this error message and are unsure of what to do
page_title: please post a message on [[Template talk:Hatnote]]
page_ns: and someone should be able to help you.

page_id: Pages that contain this error message are tracked in [[:Category:Hatnote templates with errors]].

page_id: {{Headermain|right|text[[Demogorgon (species)|DEMOGORGON (SPECIES)]]|size23|barwidth0}}[[File:Demogorgon  Chapter Eight.jpg|left|190px|linkDemogorgon (species)]]Demogorgons are predatory creatures originating from the [[Upside Down]]
page_title: an alternate dimension. Demogorgons obey the malicious [[Mind Flayer]]
page_ns: and make up part of his hive mind. Under his influence

page_title: a [[The Demogorgon|fully grown Demogorgon]] set foot in [[Hawkins]]
page_ns: Indiana after a [[Gate|gateway]] to the Upside Down was accidentally opened. This Demogorgon was eventually defeated and destroyed
revision_id: but not before it could inflict damage upon the human world. [[Will Byers]]
timestamp: a rescued victim of the Demogorgon
contributor_id: became a vessel for the Mind Flayer. Somehow
contributor_name: Wills possession allowed the Mind Flayer to unleash a swarm of adolescent Demogorgons upon Hawkins.

page_id: {{Headermain|right|text[[The Upside Down|THE UPSIDE DOWN]]|size23|barwidth0}}[[File:UpsideDownS2.png|left|210px|linkThe Upside Down]]The Upside Down is an alternate dimension existing in parallel to the human world. Most
page_ns: flora and fauna present in the dimension are linked together in a hive mind controlled by the [[Mind Flayer]]
revision_id: essentially forming an enormous superorganism. A key component of this hive mind was a species of humanoid predators

page_ns: is a recurring character in the [[Season 1|first season]] of [[Stranger Things]] and a main character in the [[Season 2|second season]].
Will was abducted by the [[Demogorgon]] and taken into an alternate dimension dubbed the [[Upside Down]]. For a week
revision_id: Will evaded the creature while his family and friends desperately searched for him. Although he was eventually rescued and returned to normal life
timestamp: his time in the Upside Down left him with a mysterious connection to the alternate realm.

page_id: [[File:Stranger Things 1x06Elevens mental void.jpg|left|200px|linkThe Void]]The Void is a visual representation of [[Eleven]]s mind while using extrasensory perception to locate other entities in different locations to her own.
The Void appears as a vast endless expanse of nothingness. The floor is covered in a thin layer of water. It is completely empty
page_title: not including Eleven herself or whatever or whoever she is trying to locate.

page_id: {{Headermain|text[[The Vanishing of Will Byers|THE VANISHING OF WILL BYERS]]|size23|barwidth0}}

[[File:The Vanishing of Will Byers S01E01 SS 001.png|left|260px|linkThe Vanishing of Will Byers]]"Chapter One: The Vanishing of Will Byers" is the first episode of [[Stranger Things|Stranger Things]] and the first episode of the [[Stranger Things/Season 1|first season]]. It was written and directed by the [[The Duffer Brothers|Duffer Brothers]] and premiered on [[Netflix]] on July 15
page_title: 2016 along with the rest of the season.

page_id: On his way home from a [[Mike Wheeler|friend]]s house
page_title: young [[Will Byers|Will]] sees [[The Monster|something terrifying]]. Nearby
page_ns: a [[Gate|sinister secret]] lurks in the depths of a [[Hawkins National Laboratory|government lab]].

The Key referred to a type of Russian machine that could open [[Portals|Gates]] to the [[Upside Down]]
page_title: though the term "Key" was also colloquially used to refer to the Gates themselves. When activated using two special keys
page_ns: the machine fired a highpowered laser beam which could open "a doorway between worlds".

column10: Eleven is feeding the rottweiler fish. The dog licks her face
column11: causing her to smile. Benny remarks that a smile looks good on her and Eleven calls him good in return. He states he knows a few people who would disagree
column12: and reveals a list of tattooed names on his arm
column13: most likely belonging to his exgirlfriends. Eleven points to a name reading Tommy
column14: saying it belongs to his little brother. Benny is confused
column15: but before he can question further
column16: he hears someone arrive in the driveway. A woman named [[Connie Frazier]] is at the door. After saying she is from Social Services
column17: Benny lets her in. Connie shoots Benny
column18: and agents swarm the restaurant. In the kitchen
column19: Agent One kills the dog when it attempts to attack him. Suddenly
column20: Eleven blasts the storage closet door open injuring the agents in the process. She laments Bennys and the dogs deaths

page_title: Nancy and Barb are waiting for Steve. He finally shows up
page_ns: but appears to be drunk and stoned. He leads Nancy away
contributor_name: and Dustin meet and set off for Mirkwood.

page_id: Steve leads Nancy to a more secluded part of the beach. He pushes her down and begins removing her clothing. Nancy is hesitant towards Steves advances
page_title: but he continues anyway. Back at the bonfire
page_ns: Barb gets tired of waiting for Nancy and decides to leave. After starting her car
revision_id: the radio cycles through various stations playing garbled
timestamp: distorted noise and the cars lights flicker. Confused
contributor_id: Barb turns the engine off. A moment later
factoids: and a highpitched sound is heard. Once the sound has faded and the lights have dimmed

page_title: Joyce is working on Wills missing poster. They are consoling each other when the phone rings. Joyce answers it
page_ns: but only hears the sound of someones breathing. She repeatedly asks who it is
revision_id: with the breathing only growing louder. At last
timestamp: a distant voice belonging to Will responds. Joyce frantically asks where he is
contributor_id: but his voice is replaced with a new
contributor_name: inhuman one. A highpitched sound emits from the receiver. Joyce drops the phone
bytes: her palm now seared. Jonathan quickly grabs the phone
factoids: but the line is now dead. A distant voice calls for help.

page_title: her nose and ears bleeding. The beach is empty but she can still hear the distant sounds of the bonfire. There is a thick fog
page_ns: and the waves seem to roll in slowly
revision_id: like time is distorted. There are pulsating growths all over the sand and blue lightning flashes in the sky. Barb hears guttural sounds coming from behind her. She turns to see a horde of shadowed figures heading towards her.

page_id: The boys are searching for Will on Mirkwood when Mike sees a figure in the middle of the road. He tries to avoid it
page_title: causing Lucas and Dustin to crash into him. Once hes back on his feet Mike shines his flashlight on the figure
page_ns: revealing it to be Eleven. A rumbling sound is heard from overhead
revision_id: making Mike look up at the sky. Joyce
contributor_id: and Hopper are looking up too. Dark silhouetted clouds roll in above the town
contributor_name: and blue lightning illuminates the sky.

page_title: saying The storm is no longer coming. Its here.

page_id: [[Stranger Things]] is a televisionformat series created by the [[The Duffer Brothers|Duffer Brothers]] released as a [[Netflix]] original series on July 15
The show takes place in the fictional town of [[Hawkins]]
page_title: [[Indiana]] in the earlytomid 1980s. The [[Season 1|first season]] revolves around the disappearance of [[Will Byers]]
page_ns: while the [[Season 2|second season explores]] the repercussions of the mysterious events of season 1. The upcoming [[Season 3|third season]] will be focusing on "forces of evil that are new."

factoids: This template is used to create hatnotes to point to a small number of other
column11: titles at the top of [[Help:Section|article sections]]. It looks like this:

page_id: Do not use this template inside the "See also" section at the end of an article
page_title: or for links to other articles or subsections of the same article within regular article text. Where subsections are linked to

page_id: Refer to the examples below to see how the template handles link targets containing section links and commas.
| label 1  label 1 | label 2  label2 | label 3  label3 | ...
| l1  label1 | l2  label2 | l3  label3 | ...
This template accepts the following parameters:

revision_id: ...  the pages to link to. At least one page name is required. Categories and files are automatically escaped with the [[Help:Colon trick|colon trick]]
timestamp: and links to sections are automatically formatted as page § section
contributor_id: rather than the MediaWiki default of page#section.

contributor_name: ...; optional labels for each of the pages to link to.

revision_id: adds the CSS class "selfref". This is used to denote selfreferences.

timestamp: suppresses the error tracking category ([[:Category:Hatnote templates with errors]]). This only has an effect if the first positional parameter (the page to link to) is omitted.

page_id: {{see also|Article#Section|label 1Custom section label}} → {{see also|Article#Section|label 1Custom section label}}
{{see also|Article1|l1Custom label 1|Article2|l2Custom label 2}} → {{see also|Article1|l1Custom label 1|Article2|l2Custom label 2}}
{{See also|Julius Caesar#Civil war|Crossing the Rubicon}} → {{See also|Julius Caesar#Civil war|Crossing the Rubicon}}
If no page names are supplied
page_title: the template will output the following message:

page_id: If you see this error message
page_title: it is for one of four reasons:

page_id: # No parameters were specified (the template code was {{see also}}). Please use {{see also|page}} instead.

page_title: but no page names were included. For example
page_ns: the template text {{see also|selfrefyes}} will produce this error. Please use (for example) {{see also|page|selfrefyes}} instead.

page_title: but it contains an equals sign (""). The equals sign has a special meaning in template code
page_ns: and because of this it cannot be used in template parameters that do not specify a parameter name. For example
revision_id: the template code {{see also|1+12|2+24}} will produce this error. To work around this
timestamp: you can specify the parameter name explicitly by using 1

page_id: # You tried to access [[Module:See also]] directly by using {{#invoke:see also|seealso|text}}. Use of #invoke in this way has been disabled for performance reasons. Please use {{see also|text}} instead.
Pages that contain this error message are tracked in [[:Category:Hatnote templates with errors]].

page_id: Due to the content and themes of [[Stranger Things]]
page_title: it is advised that users be at least 13 years or older to edit this wiki.

page_id: All users should be civil and courteous to one another. Do NOT insult users who have less experience
page_title: whose edits are not following the wikis standards
page_ns: or for having different opinions than yours.

revision_id: or any other derogatory remarks targeted towards any group of people are permitted.

page_id: No sexual or explicit content will be permitted on the wiki
page_title: unless within context of the source material (e.g. Nancy and Steves relationship).

page_id: No inappropriate or hateful comments regarding the actors and actresses will be allowed.
Users are free to customize their profiles as they see fit
page_title: as long as the content doesnt conflict with the rules on this page.

page_id: All files uploaded to the wiki for personal use on profiles should be placed in [[:Category:User files]]. If not
page_title: the user will be given a warning. If the file is still not categorized properly after the user has been warned
page_ns: the file will be deleted. All files that break the rules will be deleted without warning.

page_id: Before uploading fan content that you did not create yourself
page_title: please get permission from the original creator.

page_id: If you have discovered that something you created is being used without your consent
page_title: please contact a member of the [[Stranger Things Wiki:Staff|wikis staff]] and the file in question will be removed.

page_id: Do NOT edit another users profile without their permission.
If a users profile content does not follow the rules
page_title: please contact an admin about it.

Users are expected to follow the wiki’s editing policies. Please see the [[Stranger Things Wiki:Style Guide|Style Guide]] and [[Stranger Things Wiki:Layout Guide|Layout Guide]] for the complete explanation of editing policies.
Edits should be constructive and made with the purpose of improving an article’s content.
Do not engage in edit wars. Instead
page_title: discuss with other users or the wiki’s staff to find a solution.

page_id: Do NOT vandalize the articles. You will be blocked. You have been warned.
All comments under an article’s comment section should pertain to that article in some way.
Inappropriate comments and comments containing spam will be removed.
The Discussion Board’s guidelines can also be found [https://strangerthings.fandom.com/d/g here].
Be nice and treat people with respect. Keep discussions civil and be openminded about differing opinions.
Threads and posts that solicit upvotes will be deleted.
Impersonation of other users or famous people will not be tolerated. If you have been banned and return on a new account
page_title: your posts will be deleted and your new account(s) will be banned.

page_id: No sharing personal information about yourself or other people.
No posts about people not involved with Stranger Things.

page_ns: or vandalizing of any kind will be deleted and will lead to your account being banned.

page_id: Posts made with the sole purpose of spreading false information will be deleted.
The report feature is for posts and comments that break the guidelines on this page. Do not report posts simply because you dont like them or for having an opinion you dont agree with.

page_id: What makes an antagonist? Is Lucas an antagonist
page_title: for getting into a fight with Mike? Is Lonnie an antagonist
page_ns: for being a deadbeat? Is Joyces boss an antagonist for almost denying her advances on her paycheck? Is Mr Scotts date an antagonist for giving him the cold shoulder?

page_id: Maybe Brenner has ends that justify the means. Is the Monster truly an antagonist
page_title: or is it just eating to survive?

page_id: Calling someone an antagonist is purely a subjective moral judgement in some cases. Im not sure its a valid category
page_title: and theres definitely not a unifying factor about everyone being called an antagonist here that ties them together
page_ns: which is kinda the point of a category. [[w:User:FishTank|FishTank]] <staff /> ([[w:Message Wall:FishTank|wall]]) 03:07

page_id: : I vote to keep. In this case its not a purely subjective moral judgement
page_title: but rather explains the characters function in the story. Is Brenner pure evil? Is the monster? Perhaps not
page_ns: but thats not what the term means in the context of narrative. It just means that theyre the opposition  the ones who stand in the way of the protagonists reaching their goal. Stranger Things is a story that distinguishes between the protagonists and antagonists very clearly

page_id: : I vote to keep as well
page_title: for more or less the same reason as 80XPD: An antagonist is
revision_id: a character that functions as an obstacle that the protagonist needs to overcome
timestamp: and the division between protagonists and antagonists in Stranger Things are pretty clear cut. The fact that you can justify the actions of an antagonist and maybe even sympathize with them does not make them any less of an antagonist
contributor_id: it just makes for better storytelling (as does protagonists not always getting along
contributor_name: as in the case with Lucas). [[User:Savemejebus|SaveMeJebus]] ([[User talk:Savemejebus|talk]]) 08:26

column10: Now before you go on Judging me
column11: let me tell you this did not happen overnight.

page_id: This all took place at the end of 2017 when my brother and I finished watching Stranger Things (both seasons) somewhere in December. After finishing it
page_title: I kept having this thought in my mind that the Hawkins lab Test Subjects are all female and none of then are in Antagonistic roles (Eight is an AntiHero
page_ns: which is a far cry from Antagonist). Then I started creating this Character who is Test Subject
timestamp: with a God Complex and he is an Antagonist. But how do I make him stand out? By taking the very similarity they have
contributor_id: their nosebleeding. Tens nose doesnt bleed because he uses a drug that inhibits that part of his brain for certain amount of time and if he doesnt take it soon then his entire face will bleed (so you can say he is a Drug Addict). With this idea exploding in my head everyday
contributor_name: I decided to use it to my advantage. Thanks to a suggestion of my Brother
bytes: I created a Petition regarding it (I do not care if they use it or not as long as I get noticed by ST Cast and Crew) and it is currently sitting on over a 1000 Signattures. I also wrote a fanfiction using that character. Here are the links so do check them out.

factoids: This is my Theory for the entire 4th Season

page_title: we saw Hopper get blown up
page_ns: Eleven losing her powers and flash forward to October 1985
revision_id: we see the Byers move out with Eleven somewhere far away with promises of visiting each other on the Holidays. Then jump to Kamchatka
timestamp: Russia and we see two guards drag a prisoner towards a fully grown Demogorgon
contributor_id: and they also have an American Prisoner.

page_id: Many have theorized that Hopper is that American Prisoner and some has also theorized that its actually Brenner and Hopper is either dead or stuck in the Upside Down (judging by the ladder near the machine which was on Hoppers side). I personally want to believe all of them (except for Hopper dead theory) and I have theorized how the next Season (Stranger Things 4) might go (which also includes all the theories mentioned above except for Hopper dead theory).
Heres how I think El will get back her powers
page_title: it will probably happen because of Will. Hear me out
page_ns: Will got stuck in the Upside Down and had formed a connection with the Mind Flayer because of Eleven; now that Hopper is (supposedly) dead
revision_id: Joyce took in Eleven in her family and moved far away from Hawkins therefore Eleven and Will will form some kind of brothersister bond. And because of that bond they will have the need to protect each other. If one of the Bullies in their new school thinks (I hope) Will is gay then they would probably get a beating somewhere in front El and she unable to help will feel a strong emotion of anger and sadness and suddenly her powers reawakened.

page_id: This could also begin with a little hint where El is constantly having dreams of Hopper being in a Russian Prison with Russian Guards or hiding in the Upside Down against the Demogorgon. Of course when she tells Joyce about it
page_title: she passes it off as a Nightmare. By the end of first episode she reawakens her power and the first thing she does is to see whether her visions of Hopper were dream or not and surprisingly she finds them to be true. They return to Hawkins after the incident of Elevens power to cool it off and Eleven mentions it to everyone. Thus the entire season will go on finding and Saving Hopper from either the Russian Prison or The Upside Down. If Hopper is in the Upside Down then she might find Brenner in the Russian Prison.

The events of Season 3 of Stranger Things revolves around the Forth of July 1985.
[[File:Screen_Shot_20190713_at_10.09.53_PM.png|thumb|What phase is the moon?]]The Moon Phase and What Day of the Week is the Climax?

In the climax of this series the moon appears to be just off full or perhaps three quarters full during the Fun Fair. According to [https://mooncalendar.astroseek.com/moonphaseday6july1985 this source]
page_title: on the full moon was the 2nd July in 1985. On the 4th July is was a waning gibbous moon (just off full). The forth of July in 1985 fell on a Thursday
page_ns: was the Fun Fair held on the Thursday itself or the Saturday? The phase of the moon may give this away. What do you think is it 2 or 4 days off full? The best look at the moon is at 17:56 and 36:11 in Episode 8.

a Thursday or the Saturday after perhaps?
